  <content>
    <title>Embedding Chunking Strategies</title>

    <summary>Embedding models have token limits. Long documents must be split into chunks before embedding. The chunking strategy determines retrieval quality: wrong chunk size degrades both precision (too large — diluted context) and recall (too small — lost cross-sentence meaning).</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Token limits: OpenAI text-embedding-3-large max 8191 tokens; chunks exceeding this are silently truncated, degrading embedding quality. Chunk size directly controls retrieval precision and recall — focused chunks (256-512 tokens) surface targeted answers; larger chunks (1000-2000 tokens) provide more surrounding context for summarization tasks.</p>
      <p>An ingestion agent tokenizes and counts tokens per chunk before embedding, discards or splits chunks exceeding the model's token limit, and batches remaining chunks into groups of 50-100 for the embedding API call.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Any document corpus being ingested into a vector store for RAG retrieval.</item>
        <item>Documents longer than the embedding model's token limit (8191 for OpenAI models).</item>
        <item>When retrieval precision matters — chunk size tuning is the primary quality lever.</item>
        <item>Code search where function boundaries must be preserved.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Short single-sentence texts already within token limits — chunking adds unnecessary overhead.</item>
        <item>Structured data (tables, databases) where semantic chunking destroys row integrity — use row-level embedding instead.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="fixed-size-chunking">
      <p>Split text into fixed-size word chunks with overlap. Simple and predictable but ignores sentence and paragraph boundaries.</p>

      <rule>
        <statement>Always count tokens (not words or characters) before embedding. Use tiktoken for OpenAI models. Use len(text.split()) * 1.3 as a rough heuristic for non-OpenAI models.</statement>
        <rationale>Word-count chunking can silently exceed token limits when text contains multi-token words or subword tokenization. Silent truncation by the embedding API degrades vector quality without raising an error.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Fixed-size word chunks with overlap">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
def chunk_fixed_size(
    text: str,
    chunk_size: int = 500,
    overlap: int = 50
) -> list[str]:
    """Split text into fixed-size chunks with overlap."""
    words = text.split()
    chunks = []
    start = 0

    while start < len(words):
        end = start + chunk_size
        chunk = " ".join(words[start:end])
        chunks.append(chunk)
        start = end - overlap

    return chunks
]]></code>
        <note>Word-based overlap preserves cross-chunk context continuity. 10% overlap is typical for most use cases.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="token-based-chunking">
      <p>Split text by exact token count using the same tokenizer as the embedding model. More accurate than word-count and prevents silent truncation.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Token-based chunking with tiktoken">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import tiktoken

def chunk_by_tokens(
    text: str,
    max_tokens: int = 500,
    overlap_tokens: int = 50,
    model: str = "text-embedding-3-large"
) -> list[str]:
    """Split text by token count (more accurate)."""
    encoding = tiktoken.encoding_for_model(model)
    tokens = encoding.encode(text)
    chunks = []
    start = 0

    while start < len(tokens):
        end = min(start + max_tokens, len(tokens))
        chunk_tokens = tokens[start:end]
        chunk_text = encoding.decode(chunk_tokens)
        chunks.append(chunk_text)
        start = end - overlap_tokens

    return chunks
]]></code>
        <note>tiktoken is the canonical tokenizer for all OpenAI embedding models. Use cl100k_base encoding for text-embedding-3-* and ada-002.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="semantic-chunking">
      <p>Split at natural text boundaries (paragraphs, sentences) using LangChain's RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter. Produces semantically coherent chunks that preserve prose structure.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Semantic chunking via RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from langchain.text_splitter import RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter

def chunk_semantic(
    text: str,
    chunk_size: int = 1000,
    chunk_overlap: int = 200
) -> list[str]:
    """Split at natural boundaries (paragraphs, sentences)."""
    splitter = RecursiveCharacterTextSplitter(
        chunk_size=chunk_size,
        chunk_overlap=chunk_overlap,
        separators=["\n\n", "\n", ". ", " ", ""]
    )
    return splitter.split_text(text)
]]></code>
        <note>Separator order matters: double newlines (paragraphs) are tried first; single characters last. This preserves semantic units when possible.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="sentence-based-chunking">
      <p>Group N sentences per chunk with sentence-level overlap. Produces the highest semantic coherence for prose-heavy documents.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Sentence-based chunking with NLTK">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import nltk
nltk.download('punkt')

def chunk_by_sentences(
    text: str,
    sentences_per_chunk: int = 5,
    overlap_sentences: int = 1
) -> list[str]:
    """Split by sentences for better semantic coherence."""
    sentences = nltk.sent_tokenize(text)
    chunks = []
    start = 0

    while start < len(sentences):
        end = start + sentences_per_chunk
        chunk = " ".join(sentences[start:end])
        chunks.append(chunk)
        start = end - overlap_sentences

    return chunks
]]></code>
        <note>NLTK punkt tokenizer handles abbreviations and punctuation correctly. Download once; the model is cached locally.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="optimal-chunk-sizes">
      <p>Recommended chunk sizes by use case:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Q&amp;A RAG — 256-512 tokens, 20% overlap — focused single-topic answers</item>
        <item>Document summary — 1000-2000 tokens, 10% overlap — more surrounding context</item>
        <item>Code search — 100-200 tokens, 50% overlap — preserve function bodies</item>
        <item>Legal/Medical — 500-1000 tokens, 25% overlap — complete clauses</item>
      </list>

      <rule>
        <statement>For Q&amp;A RAG, start with 512 tokens and 10% overlap. Evaluate retrieval precision@5 on a representative test set before changing chunk size.</statement>
        <rationale>Chunk size is the primary quality lever but must be validated against actual retrieval metrics. Intuitive sizing frequently misses the optimal point by 2x in either direction.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="token-guard">
      <p>An ingestion agent must validate token counts before calling the embedding API. Texts exceeding the model limit must be split further or logged and skipped — never silently truncated by passing them raw.</p>

      <example type="good" title="Token guard before embedding API call">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
import tiktoken

enc = tiktoken.get_encoding("cl100k_base")

def guard_token_limit(text: str, max_tokens: int = 8000) -> str:
    """Truncate text to max_tokens if it exceeds the limit."""
    tokens = enc.encode(text)
    if len(tokens) <= max_tokens:
        return text
    # Truncate and decode
    return enc.decode(tokens[:max_tokens])

def prepare_chunks_for_embed(chunks: list[str], max_tokens: int = 8000) -> list[str]:
    """Apply token guard to all chunks before embedding."""
    guarded = []
    for chunk in chunks:
        token_count = len(enc.encode(chunk))
        if token_count > max_tokens:
            # Log warning; truncate to limit
            guarded.append(guard_token_limit(chunk, max_tokens))
        else:
            guarded.append(chunk)
    return guarded
]]></code>
        <note>Always apply guard before batch-embedding. Log chunks that required truncation for corpus quality audit.</note>
      </example>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Passing raw documents (entire PDFs, large HTML pages) directly to the embedding API without chunking or token counting.</description>
        <reason>OpenAI silently truncates at 8191 tokens. The resulting vector represents only the beginning of the document. Retrieval on long documents fails silently.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

